---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { BREW_INSTALL, MAC_DMG_URL, APP_VERSION } from '../consts.js';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="Installation Guide — Orcha" description="Install Orcha — download the Mac desktop app or set up the CLI from source.">
  <!-- INTRO -->
  <section class="install-intro">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h1>Installation Guide</h1>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Orcha has two parts that work together. <strong>Start with the command-line tool (CLI)</strong> —
        it’s the engine that powers orchestration inside Claude Code and Codex. Then, if you’d like a
        desktop dashboard, add the Mac app on top. The Mac app is not standalone: it needs the CLI
        installed first.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PREREQUISITES — HOMEBREW & DOCKER -->
  <section id="prereqs">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Before you begin — Claude CLI, Homebrew &amp; Docker</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Orcha works <em>through</em> Claude Code, so the <strong>Claude CLI</strong> needs to be
        installed and available first. It also installs through <strong>Homebrew</strong> (the Mac
        app store for command-line tools) and runs each project inside <strong>Docker</strong>
        (which keeps every project’s database and portal neatly isolated). If you already have all
        three, skip ahead to Step 1. Otherwise set them up first — it’s a one-time thing and takes a
        few minutes each.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">1. Install the Claude CLI</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Orcha plugs its slash-commands into <strong>Claude Code</strong>, so you need the
        <code class="inline">claude</code> command installed and working from any folder. Open the
        <strong>Terminal</strong> app (find it with Spotlight — press ⌘&nbsp;Space and type
        “Terminal”), then paste this line and press Return:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># installs the Claude CLI (Claude Code)</span>
curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash</code>
      <p class="note">
        Then confirm it’s installed <strong>globally</strong> — meaning it works from any folder, not
        just one. Open a fresh Terminal window and run <code class="inline">claude --version</code>:
        if it prints a version number you’re set. (If it instead says “command not found”, close and
        reopen Terminal and try once more.)
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">2. Install Homebrew</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Open the <strong>Terminal</strong> app (find it with Spotlight — press ⌘&nbsp;Space and type
        “Terminal”), then paste this line and press Return:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># installs Homebrew, the Mac package manager</span>
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"</code>
      <p class="note">
        When it finishes, it may print a couple of “Next steps” lines asking you to run two more
        commands so your Mac can find <code class="inline">brew</code>. Copy-paste those too — then
        you’re done.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">3. Install Docker Desktop</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        With Homebrew in place, install Docker Desktop with one command:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># installs Docker Desktop</span>
brew install --cask docker</code>
      <p class="note">
        After it installs, open <strong>Docker Desktop</strong> once from your Applications folder
        and leave it running in the background — Orcha needs Docker switched on while you work.
        Prefer a regular installer? You can also download Docker Desktop from
        <a href="https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/">docker.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLI (STEP 1 — REQUIRED) -->
  <section id="cli">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Step 1 — Install the CLI <span class="badge-req">Required</span></h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        The <code class="inline">orcha</code> command-line tool spins up each project’s private
        Postgres + portal and brings the slash commands into your AI coding agent. Everyone needs
        this — including Mac app users. You’ll need the Claude CLI, Homebrew and Docker from the
        steps above, plus Python 3.10+.
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># install the CLI with Homebrew</span>
{BREW_INSTALL}

<span class="c"># initialise orchestration inside any project</span>
orcha init --objective "Ship the thing" --as YourName</code>
      <p class="note">
        <strong>Updating:</strong> already have Orcha? Run
        <code class="inline">brew upgrade orcha</code> to get the latest CLI.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MAC DESKTOP APP (STEP 2 — OPTIONAL) -->
  <section id="mac">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Step 2 — Add the Mac app <span class="badge-opt">Optional</span></h2>
      <p class="note note-prereq">
        <strong>Install the CLI first.</strong> The Mac app is not a standalone program — it’s a
        desktop dashboard for the CLI you installed above. Without the CLI (and Docker) running,
        the app has nothing to connect to.
      </p>
      <p class="section-sub">
        The Orcha desktop app bundles the portal dashboard in a native window — containers,
        agents, tasks and a live audit trail, all in one place. Universal build for both Apple
        Silicon and Intel Macs.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href={MAC_DMG_URL}>Download Orcha {APP_VERSION} (.dmg)</a>
      </div>
      <p class="note">
        <strong>Signed &amp; notarized by Apple.</strong> Open the .dmg, drag Orcha into your
        Applications folder and launch it — it opens straight away with no security warnings.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href={base}>Back home</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STOPPING / UNINSTALLING -->
  <section id="uninstall">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Stopping or removing Orcha</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Want to pause a project, free up your machine, or remove Orcha entirely? Run these from the
        <strong>Terminal</strong>, in this order — each line undoes a bit more.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">1. Stop a running project</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Run this inside the project folder to shut Orcha down and clear that project’s local
        database and portal:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># stops the project and removes its local data</span>
orcha down -v</code>
      <p class="note note-prereq">
        <strong>This erases that project’s Orcha data</strong> (its tasks, agents and history live in
        the local database the <code class="inline">-v</code> flag wipes). Your own code and files are
        untouched — but if you just want to pause and come back later, stop here and run
        <code class="inline">orcha up</code> again when you return, rather than wiping the data.
      </p>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">2. Uninstall the Orcha CLI</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Once nothing is running, remove the command-line tool itself:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># removes the orcha command</span>
brew uninstall orcha</code>

      <h3 class="prereq-h">3. Remove the Orcha tap</h3>
      <p class="section-sub">
        Finally, drop the Homebrew “tap” that Orcha installs from, so Homebrew stops tracking it:
      </p>
      <code class="code"><span class="c"># removes the Orcha source from Homebrew</span>
brew untap open-orcha/orcha</code>
      <p class="note">
        Changed your mind? You can reinstall any time by following Step&nbsp;1 above —
        <code class="inline">{BREW_INSTALL}</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
